{{North Staffordshire Railway RDT}}

The '''North Staffordshire Railway''' (NSR) was a [[Great Britain|British]] [[railway]] company formed in 1845 to promote a number of lines in the [[Stoke-on-Trent|Staffordshire Potteries]] and surrounding areas in [[Staffordshire]], [[Cheshire]], [[Derbyshire]] and [[Shropshire]].

The company was based in [[Stoke-on-Trent]] and was nicknamed '''The Knotty'''; its lines were built to the [[standard gauge]] of {{RailGauge|UKsg}}.  The main routes were constructed between 1846 and 1852 and ran from [[Macclesfield]] to [[Norton Bridge, Staffordshire|Norton Bridge]], just north of [[Stafford]], and from [[Crewe]] to Egginton Junction, west of [[Derby]].  Within these main connections with other railway companies, most notably the [[London and North Western Railway]] (LNWR), the company operated a network of smaller lines although the total route mileage of the company never exceeded {{convert|221|mi|km|1}}.  The majority of the passenger traffic was local although a number of LNWR services from [[Manchester]] to [[London]] were operated via Stoke.  Freight traffic was mostly coal and other minerals but the line also carried the vast majority of china and other pottery goods manufactured in England.

As the NSR was surrounded by other larger railway companies, there were in the 19th century several attempts emanating from other companies or proposals from NSR shareholders to amalgamate with one or more of the other companies that adjoined it.  None of these came to fruition and the NSR remained an independent company up to 1923 when it became part of the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|London, Midland and Scottish Railway Company]].

==Before the railway==
The area of north Staffordshire known today as the [[Stoke-on-Trent|City of Stoke-on-Trent]] was already a thriving industrial area before the arrival of the railways.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=17}}  The establishment of the pottery industry and the development of coal and ironstone mines in the 18th century had provided a need for materials, most noticeably clay, to be brought into the area. A corresponding need also arose for the resulting fragile goods i.e. pottery to be taken away from the area. This need had given rise in the mid to late 18th century of the construction of the [[Trent & Mersey Canal]] (T&M) and its various branches. Opened in 1777{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=18}} it was a spectacular success and paid dividends reaching 75% in 1822.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=18}}  By 1845 this had fallen to a still impressive 30%{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=18}} despite the onset of railway development in the North West of England. In 1836 the canal carried {{convert|184500|LT|t ST|0|lk=on}} of goods away and brought in {{convert|143610|LT|t ST|0}}.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=19}}

It was the Trent & Mersey Canal company that built the first railway in north Staffordshire when in 1776{{sfnp|Jeuda|1999a|p=8}} it was granted powers to build a railway, or [[plateway]], from Caldon Low<!-- The use of this spelling is known to be controversial. Different publications and organisations use different variations e.g. the Ordnance Survey use Caldon Low for the quarries but ''Cauldon Lowe'' for the hill behind the quarries. Cauldon Low is used by several businesses in the area. Christiansen and Miller use Caldon Low and as most of the references are to the quarry not the hill or the village of Cauldon, Caldon Low is used here. --> limestone quarries to the canal basin at [[Froghall]] in the [[River Churnet#The Churnet Valley|Churnet Valley]].

==Formation of the company==
The [[Railway Mania]] of 1845 found the Potteries still without a railway, although the surrounding towns of Stafford, Crewe, Derby and Macclesfield were all connected to the fledgling railway system. The ''Staffordshire Potteries Railway'' promoted a route from [[Macclesfield]] to the [[Grand Junction Railway]] mainline at [[Norton Bridge, Staffordshire|Norton Bridge]] plus a spur to [[Crewe]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=24}}  At the same time the ''Churnet Valley Railway'' promoted a line from Macclesfield to [[Derby]] with a branch to [[Stoke-upon-Trent|Stoke]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=24}} After these two companies applied for the necessary powers to build the lines, Parliament suggested a pause of a year "to afford time for consideration and for maturing some more complete scheme for the accommodation of that important district".{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=25}}

The two companies decided to join forces to make a new approach to Parliament. They also incorporated in the scheme a proposal to join the [[Trent Valley Line|Trent Valley Railway]] into the Potteries. To do this they promoted the ''North Staffordshire or Churnet Valley and Trent Junction Railway''.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=25}}  This prospective company issued its prospectus on 30 April 1845 from offices at 1 Old Palace Yard, [[Westminster]], [[London]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=25}}  There was to be a share capital of £2,350,000 (£{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|2350000|1845|{{inflation-year|UK}}|r=0}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK}}).{{Inflation-fn|UK}} in £20 shares (117,500 shares).{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=25}}

The prospectus outlined the NSR's plans for two main lines. The ''Pottery Line'' running from a junction with the [[Manchester and Birmingham Railway|Manchester & Birmingham railway]] at [[Congleton]] to the Grand Junction Railway at [[Colwich, Staffordshire|Colwich]] was promoted, as 'giving the most ample accommodation to the towns of [[Tunstall, Staffordshire|Tunstall]], [[Burslem]], [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]], [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Hanley]], [[Stoke-upon-Trent|Stoke]], [[Fenton, Staffordshire|Fenton]], [[Longton, Staffordshire|Longton]] and [[Stone, Staffordshire|Stone]]'. The ''Churnet Line'' was to run from Macclesfield though [[Leek]], [[Cheadle, Staffordshire|Cheadle]] and [[Uttoxeter]] to join the [[Midland Railway]] line between [[Burton-upon-Trent]] and Derby forming a direct link between [[Manchester]] and Derby.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=25}}

The company was formally incorporated in April 1845 under the shorter name of the North Staffordshire Railway.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=26}}  As a way of eliminating opposition to the Company's Bills in Parliament, and to allow it to promote a line to [[Liverpool]], the company made an agreement to take over the Trent & Mersey Canal Company. This was achieved by T&M shares being swapped for [[preference share]]s in the NSR.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=26}}  These preference shares paid a guaranteed annual dividend of 5% once the entire railway was open.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=26}}  The total purchase cost of the T&M to the NSR £1,170,000.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1999b|p=7}}

On 25 November 1845 the ''Derby and Crewe Railway'' was absorbed into the NSR Scheme. This was a line that was being supported by the [[Grand Junction Railway]] (GJR) running between Derby and [[Crewe]] via Uttoxeter and Stoke. It was to eliminate the opposition of the Grand Junction company to the other NSR proposals that the NSR agreed to absorb the ''Derby and Crewe''. However part of the deal was that the proposed line from [[Kidsgrove railway station|Harecastle]] to Liverpool was abandoned. Despite having arranged to purchase the T&M canal for a considerable sum, to obtain support for the Liverpool extension the NSR agreed to the GJR demand. All that survived of the NSR Liverpool plan was the short branch to [[Sandbach]] from Harecastle.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=28}}

==Parliamentary approval and construction==
On 26 June 1846, the three NSR acts were passed with the total of £2,900,000{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=29}} in share capital being shared amongst the three lines, with seven years allowed for the completion of each line. The ''North Staffordshire Railway (Pottery Line) Act''<ref>{{Cite news |date=26 June 1846 |title=North Staffordshire Railway (Pottery Line) Act 1846 |periodical=Acts of the Parliaments of the United Kingdom |volume=1846 |issue=''c.lxxxv'' |url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/chron-tables/local/chron033 |accessdate=25 April 2009 }}</ref>  provided for the construction of the line from Macclesfield to Colwich with branches to [[Norton Bridge railway station|Norton Bridge]], Newcastle, Silverdale and Crewe. This act also vested the Trent & Mersey Canal in the NSR. Allocated capital for this work was £1,500,000. The second act, the ''North Staffordshire Railway (Harecastle and Sandbach) Act''<ref>{{Cite news |date=26 June 1846 |title=North Staffordshire Railway (Harecastle and Sandbach) Act 1846 |periodical=Acts of the Parliaments of the United Kingdom |volume=1846 |issue=''c.lxxxiv'' |url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/chron-tables/local/chron033 |accessdate=25 April 2009}}</ref> provided for the construction of the line from [[Kidsgrove railway station|Harecastle]] to [[Sandbach]], allocated capital for these works was £200,000. Finally the ''North Staffordshire Railway (Churnet Valley Line) Act''<ref>{{Cite news |date=26 June 1846 |title=North Staffordshire Railway (Churnet Valley) Act 1846 |periodical=Acts of the Parliaments of the United Kingdom |volume=1846 |issue=''c.lxxxvi'' |url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/chron-tables/local/chron033 |accessdate=25 April 2009}}</ref> authorised the construction of the line from North Rode to Burton, a branch from [[Tutbury]] to Willington Junction near Derby, and the line between Uttoxeter and Stoke;  £1,200,000 of capital was allocated to this.

To start the construction work, there was an official 'cutting of the first sod' ceremony. This took place in September 1846{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=12}} The site chosen for the ceremony was a field in [[Etruria, Staffordshire|Etruria]]. A roped off enclosure for directors was created and the remainder of the field was reserved for invited guests. A mile long procession headed by [[John Lewis Ricardo]], [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Stoke-upon-Trent (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent]] and chairman of the NSR Company, formed. On Ricardo's arrival, the crowds broke through the roped off area and Ricardo was pushed and shoved. During the actual cutting he buckled the silver spade and had difficulty removing the sod. Finally, his hat blew away.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=37}}

[[File:Cutting.jpeg|thumb|Cutting of the first sod at Etruria]]

Construction work went ahead under the supervision of the Consulting Engineer, [[George Parker Bidder]]. By February 1847 there were 1,318 men and 60 horses working between [[Macclesfield]] and Colwich and they had removed {{convert|80000|cuyd|m3}} of earth, driven {{convert|843|yd|m|0}} of tunnel heading and erected {{convert|12000|yd|m|0}} yards of fencing.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=40}}

On 2 July 1847 the ''North Staffordshire Railway Act''<ref>{{Cite news |date=2 July 1847 |title=North Staffordshire Railway Act 1847 |periodical=Acts of the Parliaments of the United Kingdom |volume=1847 |issue=''c.cviii'' |url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/chron-tables/local/chron036 |accessdate=25 April 2009 }}</ref> was passed. The act was necessary was because of problems encountered with the construction of the Crewe branch. The opportunity was taken to authorise several other deviations and small branches. It also consolidated the previous acts and importantly, forced the NSR to ensure that all lines were completed by specifying that ordinary [[dividend]]s were not to exceed 5% until the Churnet Valley and Willington lines had been opened.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=42}}

Work continued apace and by 3 April 1848 the first freight trains were run.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=44}} Passenger services started on 17 April 1848 and the first passenger train left the temporary station at Wheildon Road, Stoke, hauled by locomotive No. 1 ''Dragon'', heading for a temporary station at Norton Bridge on the [[London and North Western Railway]] (LNWR).{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=12}}  The opening of the line gave the Potteries a railway link with Birmingham and London which made it an instant success with the public. Profits for the first two months were £1,668 'exceeding expectations'.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=45}}

The remaining lines under the original Acts were opened in stages but all were completed and open by the end of 1852 when the Stoke to Newcastle and Newcastle to Knutton sections opened.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=49}} A few months after the opening of the first line, the imposing permanent station in Winton Square, Stoke was opened on 9 October 1848. [[Stoke-on-Trent railway station|Stoke station]] then became the headquarters of the NSR.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=102}}

==Later lines==
Later branches constructed in the nineteenth century included lines from Stoke-on-Trent to [[Congleton]] via [[Smallthorne]] and [[Biddulph]]; Stoke-on-Trent to [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]]; Newcastle to [[Silverdale, Staffordshire|Silverdale]], [[Keele]] and [[Market Drayton]] (junction with the [[Great Western Railway]]); [[Alsager]] to [[Audley, Staffordshire|Audley]], Leycett and Keele, and [[Rocester]] to [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=299–301}}

Also opened in the nineteenth century was the only NSR line to achieve any degree of fame, the [[Potteries Loop Line]] from [[Etruria railway station|Etruria]] via Hanley, Cobridge, Burslem, Tunstall, Pitts Hill, Newchapel and Goldenhill to [[Kidsgrove]] Liverpool Rd. Authorised in stages in 1864–5, it opened to traffic in 1873.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=299}}  Its fame came from several mentions and a description of a journey on a Burslem to Hanley train in [[Arnold Bennett|Arnold Bennett's]] ''[[The Old Wives' Tale]]''.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=292–293}}

Twentieth century construction included a branch from Leek to Cauldon Lowe via Waterhouses{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=118}} from where the {{RailGauge|2ft6in}} narrow gauge [[Leek and Manifold Valley Light Railway]] (L&MV) was constructed through the Hamps and Manifold river valleys to Hulme End near [[Hartington]]. Although the L&MV was nominally independent the NSR both worked and operated the line.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=118}}

Finally in 1910, [[Trentham Park Branch Line|a very short line]] was built from Stoke-on-Trent to Trentham Park. It was authorised as part of an alternative line to Newcastle-under-Lyme but construction work beyond Trentham was quickly abandoned owing to rising costs.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=115}}  The same act of parliament also transferred the [[Cheadle Branch Line|Cheadle Railway]] to the NSR.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=114}} The Cheadle Railway was a small local company constructed with NSR's backing, built at great cost over a period of twelve years. It was a short line from [[Cresswell, Staffordshire|Cresswell]] to [[Cheadle, Staffordshire|Cheadle]], this line, only four miles long, included a very difficult tunnel. The line was opened from Cresswell to Totmonslow 7 November 1892 and to Cheadle, 1 January 1901.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=82}}

A full list of authorisation and opening dates for sections of the NSR is [[#NSR main lines and branch lines—opening dates|given below]].

==Macclesfield, Bollington and Marple Railway==
{{Main|Macclesfield, Bollington and Marple Railway}}

The Macclesfield, Bollington and Marple Railway (MB&M) was a joint line which the NSR participated in.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=49}}  A short line of just under {{convert|11|mi|km|0}}{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=303}} it was opened with the [[Manchester, Sheffield and Lincolnshire Railway]] (MS&L) in 1869 to give the NSR to Manchester independently of the LNWR. As relationships between the NSR and the LNWR grew better the reason for the line lessened as the MB&M route to Manchester was 5 miles longer than the LNWR route.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=51}}> Both passenger and freight traffic was handled by the MS&L (or as it later became the [[Great Central Railway]]) with the buildings maintained by the NSR.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=51}}

==Running powers with other companies==
As a company with only a small route mileage the NSR made extensive use of [[Arrangements between railroads#Trackage rights|running powers]] and in exchange granted running powers to other companies.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=209}}

The earliest agreements were reached with the LNWR. In 1849 an agreement was reached where LNWR traffic could work over the NSR system but in exchange a certain amount of the LNWR London trains had to be routed via Stoke.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=58}} These Manchester to London Euston restaurant car expresses were unique in often being hauled by NSR tank engines from Manchester to Stoke-on-Trent where the LNWR express engines took over for the run via Stone, Sandon, Colwich, and the main line to [[London Euston]]. The NSR received a payment for every through passenger on these trains and employed a small army of ticket inspectors to examine and clip (with its distinctive 'P' clip) every ticket during the Stoke-on-Trent station stop.{{sfnp|Walley|2003}} The agreement did give the NSR access to destinations such as [[Llandudno]], Manchester, Stafford, [[Wolverhampton]] and [[Buxton]]. NSR goods trains were able to run to places such as Liverpool and [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=209–210}}  The LNWR also used running rights over the Uttoxeter–Ashbourne line to run through coaches from Buxton to London via Nuneaton.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=34}} As well as the running power agreements with the LNWR there was a very short joint line of {{convert|32|chain|m|0}} at Middlewood and three jointly owned stations; Ashbourne, Colwich and Macclesfield Goods.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=303}}

Equally important in terms of traffic but not as extensive in terms of route were the running power agreements with the [[Midland Railway]] (MR). For the NSR passenger traffic into Derby and Burton was authorised and good traffic as far afield as [[Wellingborough]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=209}} The arrangements with these two companies allowed the NSR to run its longest passenger service, between Derby and Llandudno. These trains only ran {{convert|44.5|mi|km|1}} on NSR rails, with {{convert|6.5|mi|km|1}} over MR but with the majority, {{convert|67.5|mi|km|1}} over the LNWR.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=209}}

In 1867, an independent local company built the [[Stafford and Uttoxeter Railway]], later incorporated into the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] (GNR).  The GNR built its [[GNR Derbyshire and Staffordshire Extension]] from [[Nottingham]] and [[Derby Friargate railway station|Derby Friargate]] via [[Mickleover]] to [[Egginton Junction railway station|Egginton Junction]] with running powers over the NSR from Etwall, through [[Uttoxeter]], to Bromshall Junction. The GNR granted the NSR running rights to [[Nottingham]], [[Colwick]], [[Leicester]] and [[Peterborough]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=209}} Apart from excursion trains to Nottingham and goods trains to Colwick, the NSR did not take advantage of these powers.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=209}}

Although the NSR had joint ownership of the MB&M with the MS&L the NSR did not have running powers over the rest of the MS&L and was content to let the MS&L handle all traffic north of Middlewood.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=211}} Finally with both the NSR and the [[Great Western Railway]] (GWR) expanding into Shropshire running rights were agreed for NSR trains to run to Hodnet and Wellington and in return GWR goods trains could run to Stoke.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=209–210}}

==Amalgamation proposals and financial strength==
There were several proposals made either to the NSR or by it, to merge or lease or sell the company to other railway companies. The first was in 1849 when the LNWR, using its financial strength, made suggestions about a merger. To avoid this the NSR had to agree to the running powers outlined above.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=58}} A further attempt in 1851 got as far as a parliamentary bill being submitted for amalgamation until the [[Select Committee (Westminster System)|select committee]] appointed to look at the bill reported against the idea.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=60}}  The LNWR made a further attempt in 1855 which failed because of concerted opposition by the MR, MS&L and GWR.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=60}}  Less than twenty years later, in 1870, these four companies all combined to look at taking over the NSR following a decision by the NSR board to sell or lease the company. The four rival companies were unable to agree on who would take what share of the NSR and the proposal floundered.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=62}}

In 1875 the MS&L proposed an amalgamation which initially found favour with the NSR board and shareholders but eventually fell through when the MS&L finances were investigated{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=62}} and it was found that the MS&L was no stronger financially than the NSR. Only two years later some NSR shareholders proposed a merger with the MR,{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=62}} the board dismissed the proposal with the chairman reminding shareholders that <blockquote>
The NSR had a small mileage and had to collect traffic for the large companies which surrounded it. They made profits from good mileages while the NSR had to do a great deal for comparatively little return.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=62}}
</blockquote>

The quote about little return was accurate. In 1877 the NSR dividend was only 2% compared with the dividend of 6% paid by the LNWR to its shareholders.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=62}} A year later the dividend fell to its lowest ever point of only 1⅝%.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=97}}  However it recovered and after 1881 never fell below 3%.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=97}}  In 1891 the NSR paid a 5% dividend for the first time, a level not to be reached again until 1913.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=128}}

In 1913 the NSR ranked as the eighteenth largest company by route mileage with {{convert|216|mi|km|0}}.{{sfnp|Jenkinson|1988|p=86}} Passenger numbers stood at 7,200,000{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=159}} and goods traffic handled by the NSR consisted of {{convert|1750000|LT|MT|0}} of goods, nearly {{convert|4000000|LT|MT|0}} of coal and coke and over {{convert|2000000|LT|MT|0}} of other minerals.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=76}}  Among the {{convert|1750000|LT|MT|0}} of goods was {{convert|150000|LT|MT|0}} of pottery, over five-sixths of the entire production in Britain.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=76}}

==Grouping==
{{details|Railways Act 1921}}
Under the [[Railways Act 1921]], the NSR was one of the eight major companies designated to form the North Western, Midland and West Scottish Group.<ref>{{Cite news|date=19 August 1921|title=Railways Act 1921|periodical=Acts of the United Kingdom Parliament |volume=1921 |issue=55 |pages=schedule 1|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/RevisedStatutes/Acts/ukpga/1921/cukpga_19210055_en_1|accessdate=28 April 2009}}</ref>  This group became the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]] (LMS).  The act came into force on 1 January 1923 but along with the [[Caledonian Railway]], the NSR amalgamation into the LMS was delayed until 1 July 1923 due to certain legal requirements not being completed by the due date.{{sfnp|Nock|1982|p=14}}

==Accidents and incidents==
*In January 1885, a [[London and North Western Railway]] express passenger train collided with a freight train near [[Stoke-on-Trent]]. One person was killed.{{sfnp|Hall|1990|p=52}}

==Other interests==
In common with most other British railway companies, the NSR decided early on that it was advantageous to carry out its own maintenance work in all departments and also to undertake much of its own new construction work. [[Stoke railway works]] were opened in 1849,{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=251}} capable of producing [[carriages]], [[wagons]] and other equipment.  Construction of [[locomotives]] followed later, commencing in 1864.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=79}}

Ownership of the Trent & Mersey canal made the NSR the biggest canal owning railway{{sfnp|Simmons|1997|p=353}} with {{convert|130|mi|km|0}} of waterways owned. The T&M owned [[Rudyard Lake]] which the NSR made use of as a leisure complex, building a golf course, in 1905, on land adjoining the lake.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1999b|p=7}}  A further area of interest, again via ownership of the T&M, was the lease on Caldon Low quarries.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1999b|p=7}}  Associated with the quarry was the {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} tramway that ran from the quarries to Froghall making the NSR the operator of lines of three different gauges.
[[File:Bucknall & Northwood Station 1933424 71025ab9.jpg|thumb|right|275px|Bucknall & Northwood Station in 1962]]

Although the NSR principally served the urban areas of the Potteries, it did promote the area for tourism, especially the [[River Churnet|Churnet Valley]] which local hoteliers had labelled as "Staffordshire's little Switzerland".{{sfnp|Kelly|1896|p=53}}  The company issued a 150-page guide called ''Picturesque Staffordshire'' to support this promotion and dispel the widespread held idea that the county was dull and bleak{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=9}} In addition to the tourist traffic generated the NSR owned three hotels; the ''[[North Stafford Hotel|North Stafford]]'' in Stoke (opposite Stoke station), the ''Churnet Valley'' in Leek and the ''Hotel Rudyard'' at Rudyard.{{sfnp|Dow|1970|p=6}}

