==Motive power and rolling stock==

===Locomotives===
{{further|Locomotives of the North Staffordshire Railway}}
NSR motive power came from a mixture of sources. Before the establishment of Stoke works there was a complete reliance on outside contractors. The first locomotives were either purchased from contractors building the line{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=78}} or firms such as [[Sharp Brothers and Company]], [[B. Hick and Sons|B. Hick and Son]], [[Kitson, Thompson and Hewitson]], the [[Vulcan Foundry]] or [[Jones and Potts]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=309}}

Originally the resident engineers were responsible for the locomotive stock and the first four holders of this post were all primarily civil engineers.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=214}}  In 1863 the new general manager, Morris, commissioned an outside report on the NSR locomotive fleet which recommended the rebuilding of 50 engines.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=78}}  By the time this report was produced a new engineer, Johnson, had been appointed.  He undertook the improvements but the results were unsatisfactory and Johnson left in 1870 after only five years in post.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=79}} The only significant event of Johnson's tenure was the building of the first engines at Stoke works when three [[0-6-0T]] engines were built in 1868.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=309}}  Johnson's successor, Dodds, fared no better as his patented wedge motion, a type of [[valve gear]], was unsuccessful. Dodds was dismissed in 1875 and a new post of locomotive superintendent created with a locomotive engineer, Angus, in charge.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=79}}  Although only in post for two years Angus replaced all the wedge motions with [[Stephenson valve gear]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=79}}

There followed a long period of locomotive construction internally with all locomotives between 1875 and 1900 coming from the company works.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=311–313}}  The vast majority of these being [[Tank locomotive|tank engines]] although a small number of [[Tender (rail)|tender engines]] were constructed.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=311–313}}  Most engines, whether tank or tender locomotives were built with either [[2-4-0]] or [[0-6-0]] wheel arrangements.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=311–313}} An urgent need for heavier goods engines prompted the company to go to contractors and a small number of 0-6-0 designs were purchased from [[Nasmyth, Wilson and Company]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=225}}  In 1903 five [[0-6-2T]] engines were purchased from Vulcan Foundry{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=227}} and with the exception of two locomotives for shunting purchased from [[Kerr Stuart]] in 1919 these were the last engines not to be built by the company at Stoke.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=233}}

Apart from engine No 1 of 1848 being named ''Dragon'' only two other NSR engines were ever named, in 1882 Class C 2-4-0 No. 55 was named ''Colin Minton Campbell'' and Class C No. 54 ''John Bramley Moore'' after the chairman and deputy chairman of the company, respectively.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=222}}

The NSR also used a small number of [[railmotor]]s with three being purchased in 1905 from [[Beyer, Peacock and Company]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=83}}  They were used on routes such as the Stoke–Newcastle service but were not a success. The vehicles did survive until grouping but had been taken out of service for some time some years earlier.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=83}} In addition to the NSR locomotives were the two engines of the Leek & Manifold and the three engines that worked the Caldon Low quarries. The former were purchased from [[Kitson and Company]] and the latter from [[Brush Traction|Henry Hughes]] and [[W. G. Bagnall]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=315}}

At grouping 196 steam locomotives including the L&MV and Caldon Low engines{{sfnp|Essery|Jenkinson|1981|pp=77–79}} were absorbed into the LMS along with the three railmotors and one battery electric locomotive. This last engine was built at Stoke in 1917 for shunting the copper works at [[Oakamoor]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=233}} Four engines under construction at Stoke in 1923 were completed and also added to the LMS stock.{{sfnp|Rowledge|1989|p=29}} Although many of the locomotives were not old, due to the LMS policy of standardisation all NSR engines had been withdrawn from service by 1939.{{sfnp|Essery|Jenkinson|1981|pp=77–79}}  The one exception was the battery electric shunting locomotive which remained in service until 1963.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=233}}

Two NSR locomotives are preserved. NSR No. 2, an 0-6-2T [[NSR New L Class|New L class]] (one of the four constructed in 1923) and the battery electric locomotive.  Both formed part of the [[List of rolling stock items in the UK National Collection|national collection]] at the [[National Railway Museum]]<ref name="NRM">{{cite web |title=NRM Collections: Locomotives |url=http://www.nrm.org.uk/OurCollection/LocomotivesAndRollingStock.aspx |publisher=National Railway Museum |location= York |year=2009 |accessdate=13 May 2009}}</ref> but in 2016 ownership of the New L class locomotive was transferred to the [[Foxfield Railway]] where the locomotive is now on display.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.national-preservation.com/threads/nsr-new-l-no-2.692013/ |title=NSR New L No 2 |date=25 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>

====Locomotive depots====
The largest [[Motive power depot|locomotive depot]] was at Stoke, with 125 engines at grouping.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=236}}  The next largest was Alsager with an allocation of 15 engines. Other NSR depots existed at Macclesfield, Derby, Uttoxeter, Burton and Crewe.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=236}}  Stoke also had sub-sheds at [[Market Drayton]], [[Leekbrook]] and Ashbourne.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=236}}  NSR engines were also sub-shedded at other companies depots, with arrangements existing at the LNWR sheds at Stafford, Liverpool Edge Hill and Manchester Longsight and the GNR shed at Nottingham Colwick.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=236}}

====Locomotive liveries====
Up to 1882 locomotives were a bright green with black and white lining with a [[Stafford knot|Staffordshire knot]] emblem on the tank or tender sides.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=222}}  Longbottom introduced a new livery of a red brown with black, yellow and [[vermilion]] lining.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=222}}  Longbottom was succeeded by Adams who changed the livery once more to a crimson shade called Madder Lake{{efn|Although called Madder Lake, the [[pigment]] was not made from the [[Rubia|Madder]] plant but from [[Cochineal#Dye|Cochineal]]. {{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=227}} }}with yellow and vermilion lining. The knot emblem was replaced by the company coat of arms and the words ''North Stafford''.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=227}}

===Coaching stock===
The NSR coaching stock was, even until grouping, predominantly four and six wheeled vehicles.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=88}} Four-wheeled carriages were the norm from the start and the last were constructed in the 1880s,{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=238}} although by then they had progressed from the unbraked coaches of the 1840s with the introduction of the [[Emergency brake (train)|communication cord]] in 1869{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=238}} and the [[Vacuum brake|simple vacuum brake]] in 1883.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=87}} The first [[bogie]] coaches were introduced in 1906{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=242}} for use on the Derby–Llandudno service{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=88}} and these were followed by further examples until 1923. By 1919 all carriages, except 13 four-wheelers used on miners trains, had been fitted with steam heating{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=244}} and a number of vehicles had been fitted with through pipes to allow use in trains equipped with [[Vacuum brake#Limitations|Westinghouse brakes]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=244}} Most carriages were constructed at Stoke but some were purchased from companies such as the [[Metro Cammell|Metropolitan Carriage, Wagon and Finance Company]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=244}}

One area were the NSR was a pioneer was in the use of electrical lighting being the largest of only three British railway companies{{efn|The others were the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway|London, Tilbury & Southend]] and the [[Great North of Scotland Railway|Great North of Scotland]]{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=241}} }} to switch from oil to electric lighting and not use any form of gas lighting.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=241}}  The first coach was fitted in 1897 and new stock constructed from 1899 had electric lighting as standard.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=241}}  Conversion of the remaining stock was slow and in 1910 there were still some oil lit carriages in service.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=88}}

====Coaching liveries====
Coaching stock was originally claret{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=245}} but in 1875 was changed to Victoria Brown and white (except for branch line trains which carried an all over Victoria Brown livery) with gold and blue lining.  Victoria Brown was the same red brown colour as Longbottom had introduced for NSR locomotives.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=245}}  In 1882 waist panels were additionally painted white.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=245}}  This colour scheme lasted until 1896 when it was changed to an overall Victoria Lake (brown) colour with gold and blue lining.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=245}} Adams changed the livery to Madder Lake in 1903 to match the locomotives, the lining became yellow and red.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=245}}  A final minor change was to paint the waist panels of first class compartments cream to distinguish them.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=246}} A constant presence was the company coat of arms being displayed on the coach sides.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=245}}

===Goods stock===
Over its life the NSR built or bought many thousands of goods wagons.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=246–247}}  Early wagons had [[Buffer (rail transport)|dumb buffers]] with [[Buffer (rail transport)|spring buffers]] being introduced from 1870.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=246–247}}  Early wagons were not of high capacity e.g. typical open wagons were only of {{convert|4|LT|MT}} capacity.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=246–247}} but capacities grew to {{convert|10|LT|MT}} on average by 1923.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|pp=246–247}}

The NSR handed over to the LMS 6,612 goods wagons of which over 5,000 were open wagons for the transport of coal and other minerals.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=88}}  This number was dwarfed by the number of wagons owned by the pits, ironworks, other industrial operations and traders in the Stoke area.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=88}}  An unusual set of wagons to be seen were the bright yellow with red lettering vans owned by the [[Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus|Barnum and Bailey]] circus who had their main English depot in Stoke.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=251}}

====Goods liveries====
Goods vehicles were painted red oxide with white lettering and a white Staffordshire knot.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=250}} The letters ''N.S.R'' with only two full stops were carried in small letters.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=250}}  From 1912 the letters were increased in size but changed to just ''N S'' with a central knot and no full stops.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=250}}

==The Knotty==
The NSR is one of the few railways to become the subject of a play. In 1966, [[Peter Cheeseman]], artistic director of The [[Victoria Theatre, Stoke]] wrote a musical documentary about the NSR called ''The Knotty''. Featured in the play were the voices of several NSR staff who had been interviewed especially for the play.<ref>{{cite web |title= Memories of The Knotty|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/nostalgia/Memoryarticle-459025-details/article.html |publisher= Staffordshire Evening Sentinel|date= 8 November 2008  |accessdate=28 April 2009}}</ref> The script with introductory notes by Cheeseman was published in 1970.{{sfnp|Syssoyeva|Proudfit|2013|p=104}} Sound recordings of the production, ''The Knotty - a musical documentary'', was released on LP by Argo Transacord (ZTR 125) in 1970 and as a digital version in 2014 it was digitised by  Transacord Digital.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Cast-Of-The-Victoria-Theatre-Stoke-On-Trent-The-Knotty-A-Musical-Documentary/release/6690925 |title=Cast Of The Victoria Theatre, Stoke-On-Trent – The Knotty (A Musical Documentary) |date=2016 |accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref>

